AASD 4015 - Group Project 1¶

Member: 1. Chun Cheong Mak (101409987) 2. Hei Yuet Lee (101409639)¶

Pneumonia is a lung disease that inflames the air sacs in the lungs and could be fatal to children and the elderly. Nowadays, medical application of deep learning is popular to relieve the problem of shortage of doctors.

In this project, two CNN models will be built for classifying the healthy lungs and infected lungs. The first model is built from sketch and the second model is built by transform learning of a pre-trained model.

After building the models, we will perform fine-tuning to the models by different techniques, like early stopping, learning rate schedule, unfreezing pretrained layers, etc.

The main reference of this project is the chapter08_intro-to-dl-for-computer-vision.ipynb, which is also the implementation of the code in Chapter 8 of Deep Learning with Python (2nd edition, Fancois Chollet) by Prof. Ran Feldesh.

The main takeaways from this notebook:

  • Preprocess and visualize the dataset
  • Build two baseline models and fine-tune them
  • Data augmnentation, dropout, adding layers, changing optimizer, early stopping, learning rate schedule and unfreezing pretrained layers are used
  • Evaluate the train accuracy, validation accuracy, test accuracy of models before and after fine-tuning
  • Evaluate the train loss, validation loss, test loss of models before and after fine-tuning

Data - Chest X-Ray Images (Pneumonia)¶

The link of Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/paultimothymooney/chest-xray-pneumonia

1. Data Preprocessing¶

After downloading and unzipping the data, there are 3 folders in chest_xray: train, test and val. There are 2 folders in each of these 3 folders: NORMAL and PNEUMONIA. To avoid data inbalance, we need to check the total number of images in NORMAL and PNEUMONIA as follows:

In [5]:
test_normal_file_list = os.listdir('chest_xray/test/NORMAL')
test_pneumonia_file_list = os.listdir('chest_xray/test/PNEUMONIA')
train_normal_file_list = os.listdir('chest_xray/train/NORMAL')
train_pneumonia_file_list = os.listdir('chest_xray/train/PNEUMONIA')
val_normal_file_list = os.listdir('chest_xray/val/NORMAL')
val_pneumonia_file_list = os.listdir('chest_xray/val/PNEUMONIA')

Obviously, there is a problem of data imbalance. The total number of normal case and pneumonia case is 1585 and 4283 respectively.

In [6]:
print('Total number of normal case:', len(test_normal_file_list)+len(train_normal_file_list)+len(val_normal_file_list))
print('Total number of pneumonia case:', len(test_pneumonia_file_list)+len(train_pneumonia_file_list)+len(val_pneumonia_file_list))

In [13]:
def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ['normal', 'pneumonia']:
        os.makedirs(f'project1/{subset_name}/{category}')
        for file in os.listdir(f'chest_xray/{category}')[start_index:end_index]:
            shutil.copyfile(src=f'chest_xray/{category}/{file}',
                            dst=f'project1/{subset_name}/{category}/{file}')

The ratio of train, validation and test is 0.8: 0.1: 0.1.

In [14]:

make_subset('test', start_index=1350, end_index=1500)

3. Model 1¶

The architecture and compilation of the model 1 are taken from chapter08_intro-to-dl-for-computer-vision.ipynb.

This is also the architecture on the page 216 of Chapter 8 of Deep Learning with Python (2nd edition, Fancois Chollet).

In [70]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

From the above evaluation, the over-fitting occurs at epoch 8. The validation loss decreases before 8 epochs. After 8 epochs, the validation loss increases largely and the validation accuracy can no longer increase significantly.

The model of epoch 8 is saved and used to predict the test_dataset. The test accuracy and loss is 0.963 and 0.106 respectively.

4. Model 2: Fine-tune the Model 1¶

To fine-tune the above Model 1, we made following modification and train a Model 2:

  • Data augmentation
  • Add more Dense layer after Flatten layer
  • Add more Dropout layer after Flatten layer
  • Use adam optimizer
  • Introduce early stopping in callbacks

Overfitting may be caused by using too few samples to train. The following data augmentation will filp the images horizontally and change the contrast of the images randomly. This augmentation will generate more training data from existing data and relieve the problem of over-fitting.

In [79]:
data_augmentation = keras.Sequential(
    [
        layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
        layers.RandomContrast(0.2)
    ]
)

Two Dense layers with 64 and 16 neurons are added after Flatten layer to increase the accuracy. At the same time, three Dropout layers with 0.5 are added to avoid over-fitting.

In [80]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = layers.Dense(64, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = layers.Dense(16, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

adam combines the ideas of momentum optimization and RMSProp and the performance should be better or almost the same.

In [81]:
model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy",
              optimizer="adam",
              metrics=["accuracy"])

Early stopping with 10 patience is added and the training will stop after 10 epochs without improvement in validation loss. It is used to stop the training when over-fitting happens.

In [20]:
early_stopping_cb = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)
In [83]:
callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="saved_model/model_2.h5",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss"),
        early_stopping_cb
]

history = model.fit(
    train_dataset,
    epochs=80,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=callbacks)

  • Use adam optimizer

The reasons of using above modification are same as the reasons mentioned in Section 4.

7. VGG16 Model 3: Fine-tune the VGG16 Model 2 with Learning Rate Schedule and Unfreezing Pretrained Layers¶

To futher fine-tune the VGG16 Model 2, we made following modification:

  • Freeze the base layer until the forth from the end
  • Introduce learning rate scheduler

Below exponential decay function is taken from Chapter 11 of Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras, and TensorFlow (3nd edition, Aurlien Gron).

In [21]:
conv_base.trainable = True
for layer in conv_base.layers[:-4]:
    layer.trainable = False
In [22]:
def exponential_decay(lr0, s):
    def exponential_decay_fn(epoch):
        return lr0 * 0.1**(epoch / s) 
    return exponential_decay_fn

To achieve the a better result, exponential scheduling is used to adjust the learning rate during the training. The learning rate will gradually drop by a factor of 10 every s steps.

In order to prevent from overfitting very quickly, the initial learning rate will be set to very small.

In [24]:
exponential_decay_fn = exponential_decay(lr0=0.00001, s=80)
lr_scheduler = keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(exponential_decay_fn)
In [25]:
model_vgg.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy",
              optimizer="adam",
              metrics=["accuracy"])
In [26]:
callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="saved_model/model_vgg_3.h5",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss"),
        lr_scheduler,
        early_stopping_cb
]

The model of epoch 22 is saved and used to predict the test dataset. The test accuracy is 0.970, while the test loss improved from 1.974 to 1.064. An improvement in test loss can be found after the fine-tuning.

8. Summary¶

The test accuracy and loss of Model 1 in Section 3 is 0.963 and 0.106 respectively.

The test accuracy and loss of Model 2 in Section 4 is 0.973 and 0.091 respectively.

The summary of all models using transfer learning:


| VGG16 Model | Data Augmentation | Early Stopping | Freeze layers | Optimizer | Initial Learning Rate | Learning rate schedule | Test Accuracy | Test loss | |-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----| | 1 | No | No | All | RMSprop | 0.001 | No | 0.967 | 2.222 | | 2 | Yes | Yes | All | Adam | 0.001 | No | 0.970 | 1.974 | | 3 | Yes | Yes | Freeze until the 4th from last | Adam | 1e-5 | Yes | 0.970 | 1.064 |

The Model 2 in Section 4 outperforms all the models using transfer learning. The possible reason is that VGG16 is already an older model. Changing to other newer pretrained models may improve the performance in transfer learning.
